          Programming note  for Elon Musk:=C2=A0Don=E2=80=99t read the next=
 programming note, skip down, there=E2=80=99s a whole section about your tw=
eets! Poop emojis and everything! Skip the boring stuff and go straight the=
re!=C2=A0
Programming note for everyone else: This is the last Money Stuff of 2023. P=
robably. Unless Elon buys OpenAI or whatever. I=E2=80=99ll be back in Janua=
ry. Thanks for reading and=C2=A0have a great holiday season.

 =20
   =20
      LNG contracts
   =20
 =20

I am not, by any means, an expert in liquefied natural gas. My background i=
s in financial instruments, stocks and bonds and derivatives on stocks and =
bonds. The way that, for instance, stock options work is that, if I agree t=
o sell you XYZ stock at $40 at your option, and in a month you exercise the=
 option and hand over the $40, I really do have to give you the stock. Even=
 if it=E2=80=99s trading at $60. Obviously I=E2=80=99d rather sell the stoc=
k at $60 to someone else, but I already sold you that option, and I am boun=
d by it. If I sell a Treasury bond futures contract, I have to deliver a Tr=
easury bond at the futures price, even if the price has gone up and I could=
 sell it for more elsewhere.=C2=A0
Oh, of course, there are situations where people find ways to get out of th=
eir contracts.=C2=A0(And there are stock-related transactions=C2=A0that are=
 not ordinary-course trading =E2=80=94=C2=A0mergers, for instance =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and that are considerably more breakable.) But for the most part ther=
e is a broadly effective=C2=A0apparatus to make stock and bond=C2=A0trades =
binding, so binding that it rarely even occurs to anyone to break them. No =
stock options trader calls their lawyer to be like =E2=80=9Cman this stock =
really went up a lot, can I just not deliver it into the call options I sol=
d?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
A lot of commodities trading also works like this. If you sell aluminum fut=
ures, and the price of aluminum then doubles, you can=E2=80=99t just be lik=
e =E2=80=9Cnah I=E2=80=99d rather sell this aluminum to someone else at the=
 current price.=E2=80=9D That futures contract really is binding, in that y=
ou have to either deliver the aluminum or=C2=A0pay the current price of the=
 aluminum to get out of the deal. Selling aluminum futures is a bet that th=
e price of aluminum won=E2=80=99t go up, and everyone understands it that w=
ay, and the bet is enforceable.=C2=A0There is a clearinghouse that collects=
 from losers and pays winners, and standardized contracts and market expect=
ations that you=E2=80=99ll pay. Again,   sometimes things go wrong, but tho=
se are exceptional cases that everyone gets upset about.
By comparison, =E2=80=9Cphysical commodities trading=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 get=
ting stuff out of the ground, loading it on ships, delivering it to custome=
rs and getting paid =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the Wild West. On the one hand, it so=
rt of looks like stock and bond and commodity-futures markets: It is a fina=
ncialized global market, with fast-moving professional traders linked to ea=
ch other by computers, and with volatile prices that move rapidly in respon=
se to events, where you can make a fortune by betting the right way.=C2=A0O=
n the other hand, the=C2=A0stuff=C2=A0you are trading does not live on a co=
mputer:=C2=A0You are moving ships around, and if you say a ship will go to =
one place and it instead goes to another place, there is only so much anyon=
e can do about it. There is no clearinghouse, no way to just adjust the tra=
des on the computer to make everything right. The stuff either goes somewhe=
re, or it goes somewhere else.
And so if you are a liquefied natural gas trader company, and you sell LNG =
in long-term fixed-price contracts that require you to deliver a ship full =
of LNG to a specific port every month at a fixed price, and then the price =
of LNG goes up a lot, and you=E2=80=99d rather ignore your contract and sel=
l your ship=C2=A0full of LNG to someone else at the current higher price =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean, empirically, that does seem to happen? The condition=
s are favorable for opportunism:
=09There=E2=80=99s no central clearinghouse enforcing any rules, so if you =
hose one customer all that happens is that that customer is mad at you (and=
 sues): You can keep trading with everybody=C2=A0else.=09Instead of standar=
dized futures contracts enforced by a central clearinghouse, every deal is =
a complicated bilateral negotiation, so even when the customer sues, you ca=
n probably point to some provision=C2=A0in the contract, or some unusual=C2=
=A0circumstance, that justifies you not delivering the gas.=09It=E2=80=99s =
a global commodity market, so (1) it=E2=80=99s easy for you to find a new c=
ustomer at the current higher price and (2)=C2=A0even if the old customer i=
s mad at you, they will probably keep buying gas from you if your price is =
$0.01 below everyone else=E2=80=99s.=09LNG prices have been pretty volatile=
, driven by things like Covid-19 and Russia=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine, =
so it=E2=80=99s entirely possible that you agreed to a contract at a low pr=
ice, and now the price is high, and you are tempted to break it.

And so we have   talked a few   times about Venture Global LNG, an LNG prod=
ucer in Louisiana that entered into long-term fixed-price contracts to sell=
 its gas to customers like BP and Shell, and then =E2=80=94=C2=A0when LNG p=
rices went up a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0decided to instead sell its gas on the s=
pot market to other buyers at much higher prices. The jilted customers have=
  complained bitterly to everyone who will listen, and have gone to arbitra=
tion to force Venture Global to give them the gas, and Venture Global has b=
een like =E2=80=9Cnyah nyah, see you in court, technically our contract all=
ows us to do this.=E2=80=9D They might even be right! The contract apparent=
ly requires Venture Global to start fulfilling the long-term contracts when=
 its production plant is complete, and the plant is not yet complete. It is=
 complete enough to produce LNG and sell it on the spot market, sure, but i=
t is not completely complete.=C2=A0I   joked that the facility is =E2=80=9C=
just about finished, but they [didn=E2=80=99t], like, paint one last rivet.=
=E2=80=9D Favorable for opportunism!
Today Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Stephen Stapczynski and Faseeh Mangi have a =
story about how Gunvor Group Ltd. and Eni SpA entered into long-term LNG su=
pply contracts with Pakistan, obligating them to deliver gas to Pakistan at=
 fixed prices over=C2=A0multi-year terms, and then started missing deliveri=
es when the spot price of LNG shot up. Pakistan went to them with reasonabl=
e complaints like =E2=80=9Cwe really need this gas, and we signed a binding=
 contract obligating you to deliver it to us at a fixed price,=E2=80=9D and=
 the suppliers largely came up with excuses that do technically seem to wor=
k. With the result that:
=09Pakistan had to go buy gas in the spot market at much higher prices, and=
=09Gunvor and Eni got to go=C2=A0sell=C2=A0gas in the spot market at much h=
igher prices.

What sort of excuses? Well, a big one is=C2=A0force majeure:=C2=A0If the pl=
ants producing the LNG break down and the suppliers can=E2=80=99t get the g=
as, they don=E2=80=99t have to deliver it. This is not, you might think, an=
 excuse that would allow for much opportunism: If the plants break down and=
 the suppliers can=E2=80=99t get the gas, then they can=E2=80=99t resell it=
 on the spot market for a profit. But that=E2=80=99s not quite right:

Gunvor cited a =E2=80=9Cforce majeure,=E2=80=9D a legal term for an unavoid=
able event that makes it impossible to fulfill a contract. Specifically it =
blamed an outage at a plant in Equatorial Guinea, a tiny, hydrocarbon-rich =
Central African dictatorship. ...
That justification from Gunvor, as well as the earlier statement by Eni abo=
ut production in Egypt, took advantage of another part of Pakistan=E2=80=99=
s contracts. Unlike other LNG deals, which stipulate where a supplier will =
obtain the gas it=E2=80=99s selling, the Pakistani agreements said shipment=
s could come from anywhere within Gunvor=E2=80=99s and Eni=E2=80=99s global=
 portfolios. Pakistani officials have said they believed this would insulat=
e them from disruptions, by allowing the companies to provide any gas they =
could source.
In their communications with Pakistan, people with knowledge of the discuss=
ions say, Gunvor and Eni turned that logic on its head, arguing that becaus=
e no source was specified, a disruption anywhere gave them the right to can=
cel delivery. Problems in Equatorial Guinea therefore qualified as a force =
majeure, even though Gunvor rarely shipped gas from the plant to Pakistan. =
...
This was a novel interpretation of contract terms. =E2=80=9CIt is not typic=
ally sufficient for a seller to simply say, =E2=80=98My unrelated project o=
n the other side of the world that has no connection to this contract is do=
wn, and therefore that=E2=80=99s force majeure under this contract,=E2=80=
=99=E2=80=8A=E2=80=9D says Jessica Ham, a special counsel at US law firm Ba=
ker Botts who=E2=80=99s advised clients on LNG deals. =E2=80=9CThe buyer mi=
ght have the ability to claim that this event is unrelated, and it doesn=E2=
=80=99t actually prevent you from performing, which is a key element of a f=
orce majeure claim.=E2=80=9D

Intuitively, if Gunvor has plans to source 100 cargoes of LNG, and one plan=
t anywhere in the world shuts down and it can only get 99 cargoes, it can s=
ay =E2=80=9Cwhoops, that was Pakistan=E2=80=99s cargo, it=E2=80=99s impossi=
ble for us to get it to them=E2=80=9D and sell the other 99 cargoes at the =
higher spot price. Your binding long-term contract is the=C2=A0first=C2=A0o=
ne you drop, if the price has gone up.
Meanwhile the enforcement mechanism is not that strong. Here is an anecdote=
 about an Eni delivery in December 2020:

The Italian company said it would deliver only part of its LNG shipment for=
 the following month, explaining that an unnamed supplier had failed to mak=
e its own delivery. =E2=80=A6
In fact, say people with knowledge of the situation, a team of lawyers had =
earlier told Azzimonti that Pakistan was a =E2=80=9Cmarginal customer=E2=80=
=9D; shortchanging it wouldn=E2=80=99t risk a blacklisting by a major impor=
ter. Meanwhile, an early winter cold snap was pushing up gas demand in East=
 Asia. From November 2020 to January 2021, spot prices would jump more than=
 400%, increasing the value of a shipment from about $20 million to $100 mi=
llion or more=E2=80=94as long as it was sold to a spot buyer.
Pakistan=E2=80=99s agreement stipulated that in the event of a missed or pa=
rtial shipment, Eni would pay a penalty equal to 30% of the value of the un=
delivered cargo, calculated on the basis of the long-term contract. While r=
icher importers can demand compensation of as much as 100%, that was the st=
iffest fine Pakistan could get suppliers to accept, says Imran Maniar, the =
managing director of distributor Sui Southern Gas Co. Propose anything high=
er, he says, and =E2=80=9Cpeople don=E2=80=99t really want that in the clau=
se.=E2=80=9D In this case the penalty amounted to just $2.8 million, pocket=
 change in the energy business.
Under the terms of Eni=E2=80=99s contract, it didn=E2=80=99t have to provid=
e details about the supplier default. But even after telling Pakistan it la=
cked sufficient gas to meet its commitments, according to a person with dir=
ect knowledge of the transaction, Eni sold an LNG shipment elsewhere at the=
 spot price of roughly $100 million.

If prices have jumped 400%, and you pay a penalty of 30% of the contract pr=
ice to skip a delivery, then you have the choice of selling under the contr=
act for $100 or selling in the spot market for $500 and paying a $30=C2=A0p=
enalty, for a net of $470. You pay the penalty. Whereas in listed commodity=
 markets, the clearinghouse-enforced norm is that you pay the buyer, not 30=
% or even 100% of the contract price, but 100% of the spot price:=C2=A0You =
pay them $500, which they use to go get the commodity at the current price.
  [1]

Also bad move by Pakistan here:

In Islamabad, Pakistani officials had concluded Gunvor was looking for a wa=
