Speaking of the credit risk of deferred comp. This past weekend, extremely =
good baseball player Shohei Ohtani signed a 10-year, $700 million contract =
to play for the Los Angeles Dodgers. This has become a major item of financ=
ial news because (1) sports and (2)   the contract is weird: Ohtani will ac=
tually be paid $2 million a year for the 10 years that he plays for the Dod=
gers, and will then get $68 million a year for the=C2=A0following=C2=A010 y=
ears, starting in 2034, when he does=C2=A0not=C2=A0play for them.
The reason for this, as far as I can tell, is basically to free up more mon=
ey=C2=A0now=C2=A0for the Dodgers to spend on other good players, so that th=
ey can be good and win the World Series while Ohtani plays for them. After =
that, they can just write him huge checks for a decade and have less money =
to spend on good players, but he won=E2=80=99t be there anymore, and probab=
ly the executives who signed him won=E2=80=99t be there anymore (they=E2=80=
=99ll retire after winning all those World Series), so whatever. This is a =
well-known form of calculation in the financial world, so much so that it h=
as its own initialism, IBGYBG, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll be gone, you=E2=80=99l=
l be gone.=E2=80=9D
A secondary reason is I guess that Ohtani will be earning $2 million a year=
 while living in=C2=A0California and paying high taxes, and then he will be=
 earning $68 million a year when he no longer needs to live in California a=
nd can pay low taxes. (One reader suggested to me that California should tr=
y to tax him now on the   unrealized up-front value of his contract, heh.)=
=C2=A0
A possible third reason is, you know, people seem to like having large head=
line contract values? Winning a World Series is nice, but winning the game =
of Getting Paid the Most also seems to be important. Structuring the contra=
ct in this way allows the Dodgers to pay a large headline number at a disco=
unted price, which probably makes everyone happy.
Anyway there are various interesting things to say about this contract as a=
 bet on inflation and  interest rates and taxes, but my colleague John Auth=
ers already said them, so I will refer you to   his column. But a number of=
 readers have asked me about the credit risk=C2=A0of the contract: Substant=
ially all of Ohtani=E2=80=99s money comes in the form of payments from the =
Dodgers 10 to 20=C2=A0years from now, and what if they default? What if the=
y don=E2=80=99t make enough money to pay him? What if he retires in 2034, t=
hey have no money to spend on good players (because they are paying him) an=
d they can=E2=80=99t sell enough tickets to pay his deferred comp?
I don=E2=80=99t have a great answer. Major League Baseball, and its players=
, have definitely thought about this. The current  Collective Bargaining Ag=
reement=C2=A0has a provision (Article XVI) covering deferred compensation, =
which provides that deferred compensation =E2=80=9Cmust be fully funded by =
the Club, in an amount equal to the present value of the total deferred com=
pensation amount,=E2=80=9D within two years after it was earned. In Ohtani=
=E2=80=99s case I think this means that the Dodgers have to fund roughly $4=
6 million a year starting in 2026.
  [3]
=C2=A0=E2=80=9CFund=E2=80=9D means that the Dodgers have to set aside =E2=
=80=9Cunencumbered assets comprising cash or cash equivalents and/or regist=
ered and unrestricted readily marketable securities=E2=80=9D that are =E2=
=80=9Cexclusively for the uses and purposes of satisfying the deferred comp=
ensation obligation.=E2=80=9D So while he is playing, they will need to put=
 aside money to pay him, and I suppose if they don=E2=80=99t he can go find=
 a higher (or, lower but more creditworthy) bidder.
  [4]

On the other hand the CBA does not require the=C2=A0money to be held in esc=
row for him: It=E2=80=99s just money on the Dodgers=E2=80=99 balance sheet,=
 =E2=80=9Csubject to the claims of the Club=E2=80=99s general creditors.=E2=
=80=9D Though perhaps his contract has stricter terms. Otherwise, Ohtani=E2=
=80=99s bet is something like =E2=80=9Cif the Dodgers set aside the money f=
or me, I=E2=80=99ll probably get it, because it=E2=80=99s not like baseball=
 teams have a ton of liabilities=C2=A0other=C2=A0than deferred comp, so eve=
n if they go bankrupt I=E2=80=99ll be the main claimant on that pot of mone=
y.=E2=80=9D Which is, you know, probably fine? Not ironclad? Not necessaril=
y a calculation that I would bet half a billion dollars on but I am, for a =
great many reasons, not a successful professional athlete.
How would you hedge this risk? You can=E2=80=99t really short a baseball te=
am, or buy credit default swaps. You could buy index credit default swaps t=
o hedge against widespread credit defaults, but that=E2=80=99s not really w=
hat you want: The bad state of the world here is not so much =E2=80=9Ca lot=
 of malls go bankrupt=E2=80=9D as it is =E2=80=9Cbaseball stops being popul=
ar in the US.=E2=80=9D If I were him I=E2=80=99d buy, like, Manchester Unit=
ed stock as a hedge.
Also the other obvious question here is, what if Ohtani would like to live =
on more than $2 million a year, now? Sure it is nice to have a $680 million=
 nest egg for retirement, but he is a famous successful baseball player,=C2=
=A0shouldn=E2=80=99t he be having more than $2 million worth of fun now? I =
wonder if he can get a bank to lend him money against that $680 million?
  [5]
 Maybe the bank can figure out the credit risk.

