ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  times</a> a=
bout Venture Global LNG, an LNG producer in Louisiana that entered into lon=
g-term fixed-price contracts to sell its gas to customers like BP and Shell=
, and then =E2=80=94=C2=A0when LNG prices went up a lot =E2=80=94=C2=A0deci=
ded to instead sell its gas on the spot market to other buyers at much high=
er prices. The jilted customers have <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnAuY29tL2VuX3VzL3VuaXRl=
ZC1zdGF0ZXMvaG9tZS9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2VzL2JwLXN0YXRlbWVudC1vbi1pdHMtZmV=
yYy1jb21wbGFpbnQtYWdhaW5zdC12ZW50dXJlLWdsb2JhbC5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB92b123a2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> complained bitterly</a> to everyone who will listen,=
 and have gone to arbitration to force Venture Global to give them the gas,=
 and Venture Global has been like =E2=80=9Cnyah nyah, see you in court, tec=
hnically our contract allows us to do this.=E2=80=9D They might even be rig=
ht! The contract apparently requires Venture Global to start fulfilling the=
 long-term contracts when its production plant is complete, and the plant i=
s not yet complete. It is complete <em>enough</em> to produce LNG and sell =
it on the spot market, sure, but it is not <em>completely</em> complete.=C2=
=A0I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.2573=
98/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItMDYv=
d2hvLWdldHMtcGFpZC1mb3Itbm90LWN1dHRpbmctZG93bi10cmVlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjE0MjN=
fTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdG=
VybT0yMzEyMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC426b=
cb9e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  joked</a> that the facility is =E2=80=9Cjust about finished=
, but they [didn=E2=80=99t], like, paint one last rivet.=E2=80=9D Favorable=
 for opportunism!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDIzLWhvdy1jb21tb2RpdHktdHJhZGVycy1zd2l0Y2hl=
ZC1vZmYtcGFraXN0YW4tZW5lcmd5Lz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWV=
kaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMTQmdXRtX2NhbX=
BhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7356922a" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Stephen St=
apczynski and Faseeh Mangi have a story</a> about how Gunvor Group Ltd. and=
 Eni SpA entered into long-term LNG supply contracts with Pakistan, obligat=
ing them to deliver gas to Pakistan at fixed prices over=C2=A0multi-year te=
rms, and then started missing deliveries when the spot price of LNG shot up=
. Pakistan went to them with reasonable complaints like =E2=80=9Cwe really =
need this gas, and we signed a binding contract obligating you to deliver i=
t to us at a fixed price,=E2=80=9D and the suppliers largely came up with e=
xcuses that do technically seem to work. With the result that:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Pakistan had to go buy gas in the spo=
t market at much higher prices, and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">Gunvor and Eni got to go=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>gas in the spot market a=
t much higher prices.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What sort of excuses? Well, a big one is=C2=A0=
<em>force majeure:=C2=A0</em>If the plants producing the LNG break down and=
 the suppliers can=E2=80=99t get the gas, they don=E2=80=99t have to delive=
r it. This is not, you might think, an excuse that would allow for much opp=
ortunism: If the plants break down and the suppliers can=E2=80=99t get the =
gas, then they can=E2=80=99t resell it on the spot market for a profit. But=
 that=E2=80=99s not quite right:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gunvor cited a =E2=80=9Cforce majeure,=E2=80=
=9D a legal term for an unavoidable event that makes it impossible to fulfi=
ll a contract. Specifically it blamed an outage at a plant in Equatorial Gu=
inea, a tiny, hydrocarbon-rich Central African dictatorship. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That justification from Gunvor, as well as the=
 earlier statement by Eni about production in Egypt, took advantage of anot=
her part of Pakistan=E2=80=99s contracts. Unlike other LNG deals, which sti=
pulate where a supplier will obtain the gas it=E2=80=99s selling, the Pakis=
tani agreements said shipments could come from anywhere within Gunvor=E2=80=
=99s and Eni=E2=80=99s global portfolios. Pakistani officials have said the=
y believed this would insulate them from disruptions, by allowing the compa=
nies to provide any gas they could source.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In their communications with Pakistan, people =
with knowledge of the discussions say, Gunvor and Eni turned that logic on =
its head, arguing that because no source was specified, a disruption anywhe=
re gave them the right to cancel delivery. Problems in Equatorial Guinea th=
erefore qualified as a force majeure, even though Gunvor rarely shipped gas=
 from the plant to Pakistan. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was a novel interpretation of contract te=
rms. =E2=80=9CIt is not typically sufficient for a seller to simply say, =
=E2=80=98My unrelated project on the other side of the world that has no co=
nnection to this contract is down, and therefore that=E2=80=99s force majeu=
re under this contract,=E2=80=99=E2=80=8A=E2=80=9D says Jessica Ham, a spec=
ial counsel at US law firm Baker Botts who=E2=80=99s advised clients on LNG=
 deals. =E2=80=9CThe buyer might have the ability to claim that this event =
is unrelated, and it doesn=E2=80=99t actually prevent you from performing, =
which is a key element of a force majeure claim.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively, if Gunvor has plans to source 100=
 cargoes of LNG, and one plant anywhere in the world shuts down and it can =
only get 99 cargoes, it can say =E2=80=9Cwhoops, that was Pakistan=E2=80=99=
s cargo, it=E2=80=99s impossible for us to get it to them=E2=80=9D and sell=
 the other 99 cargoes at the higher spot price. Your binding long-term cont=
ract is the=C2=A0<em>first=C2=A0</em>one you drop, if the price has gone up=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile the enforcement mechanism is not tha=
t strong. Here is an anecdote about an Eni delivery in December 2020:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Italian company said it would deliver only=
 part of its LNG shipment for the following month, explaining that an unnam=
ed supplier had failed to make its own delivery. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, say people with knowledge of the situ=
ation, a team of lawyers had earlier told Azzimonti that Pakistan was a =E2=
=80=9Cmarginal customer=E2=80=9D; shortchanging it wouldn=E2=80=99t risk a =
blacklisting by a major importer. Meanwhile, an early winter cold snap was =
pushing up gas demand in East Asia. From November 2020 to January 2021, spo=
t prices would jump more than 400%, increasing the value of a shipment from=
 about $20 million to $100 million or more=E2=80=94as long as it was sold t=
o a spot buyer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pakistan=E2=80=99s agreement stipulated that i=
n the event of a missed or partial shipment, Eni would pay a penalty equal =
to 30% of the value of the undelivered cargo, calculated on the basis of th=
e long-term contract. While richer importers can demand compensation of as =
much as 100%, that was the stiffest fine Pakistan could get suppliers to ac=
cept, says Imran Maniar, the managing director of distributor Sui Southern =
Gas Co. Propose anything higher, he says, and =E2=80=9Cpeople don=E2=80=99t=
 really want that in the clause.=E2=80=9D In this case the penalty amounted=
 to just $2.8 million, pocket change in the energy business.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under the terms of Eni=E2=80=99s contract, it =
didn=E2=80=99t have to provide details about the supplier default. But even=
 after telling Pakistan it lacked sufficient gas to meet its commitments, a=
ccording to a person with direct knowledge of the transaction, Eni sold an =
LNG shipment elsewhere at the spot price of roughly $100 million.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If prices have jumped 400%, and you pay a pena=
lty of 30% of the contract price to skip a delivery, then you have the choi=
ce of selling under the contract for $100 or selling in the spot market for=
 $500 and paying a $30=C2=A0penalty, for a net of $470. You pay the penalty=
. Whereas in listed commodity markets, the clearinghouse-enforced norm is t=
hat you pay the buyer, not 30% or even 100% of the contract price, but <em>=
100% of the spot price:=C2=A0</em>You pay them $500, which they use to go g=
et the commodity at the current price.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also bad move by Pakistan here:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Islamabad, Pakistani officials had conclude=
d Gunvor was looking for a way to prematurely end the contract, which had b=
een due to expire in July. Seeking to cut their losses, they figured they s=
hould try to recoup about $10 million they believed the company owed them a=
s a result of a separate dispute over port fees. Pakistan therefore reduced=
 its payment for Gunvor=E2=80=99s February 2022 LNG shipment by the same am=
ount.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The officials had inadvertently given Gunvor a=
n even cleaner exit. Pakistan soon received a letter from Gunvor=E2=80=99s =
lawyers demanding the rest of the money. It refused to pay; about a week la=
ter, with gas prices in Europe near an all-time high, Gunvor gave notice th=
at it was terminating the contract.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company was within its rights to cancel th=
e deal. But LNG agreements worth hundreds of millions of dollars aren=E2=80=
=99t usually scrapped over a single payment dispute, or so quickly.=C2=A0</=
p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No no no, this agreement=C2=A0<em>wasn=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0</em>scrapped over a single payment dispute! It was scrapped over=
, the price went up! Pakistan held back the $10 million thinking that this =
was a commercial contract that was part of a long-term relationship where e=
veryone was trying to get the best result. But actually it was a trade, and=
 the price had moved against Gunvor, and if you gave it an excuse to get ou=
t of the trade it would. And it did.</p>
