<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Speaking of the credit risk of deferred comp. =
This past weekend, extremely good baseball player Shohei Ohtani signed a 10=
-year, $700 million contract to play for the Los Angeles Dodgers. This has =
become a major item of financial news because (1) sports and (2) <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9lbi9uZXdzL3RocC8yMDIzLTEyLTExL29odGFuaS1zLWRvZGdlcnM=
tY29udHJhY3QtaGFzLTY4MC1taWxsaW9uLWRlZmVycmVkLWxvd2VyaW5nLXRheC12YWx1ZS10by=
00Ni1taWxsaW9uLWFubnVhbGx5P2VtYmVkZGVkLWNoZWNrb3V0PXRydWUmc3JlZj0xa0pWTnFuV=
Q/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4deb3ae3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  the contract is weird</a>: O=
htani will actually be paid $2 million a year for the 10 years that he play=
s for the Dodgers, and will then get $68 million a year for the=C2=A0<em>fo=
llowing=C2=A0</em>10 years, starting in 2034, when he does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=
=A0</em>play for them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reason for this, as far as I can tell, is =
basically to free up more money=C2=A0<em>now=C2=A0</em>for the Dodgers to s=
pend on other good players, so that they can be good and win the World Seri=
es while Ohtani plays for them. After that, they can just write him huge ch=
ecks for a decade and have less money to spend on good players, but he won=
=E2=80=99t be there anymore, and probably the executives who signed him won=
=E2=80=99t be there anymore (they=E2=80=99ll retire after winning all those=
 World Series), so whatever. This is a well-known form of calculation in th=
e financial world, so much so that it has its own initialism, IBGYBG, =E2=
=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll be gone, you=E2=80=99ll be gone.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A secondary reason is I guess that Ohtani will=
 be earning $2 million a year while living in=C2=A0California and paying hi=
gh taxes, and then he will be earning $68 million a year when he no longer =
needs to live in California and can pay low taxes. (One reader suggested to=
 me that California should try to tax him now on the <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItMDQvd2hvc2UtaW5jb21lLWRvLXlvdS1=
wYXktdGF4ZXMtb24_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIxNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbC=
Z1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMxMjE0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25le=
XN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB530db293" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  unrealized up-front va=
lue of his contract</a>, heh.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A possible third reason is, you know, people s=
eem to like having large headline contract values? Winning a World Series i=
s nice, but winning the game of Getting Paid the Most also seems to be impo=
rtant. Structuring the contract in this way allows the Dodgers to pay a lar=
ge headline number at a discounted price, which probably makes everyone hap=
py.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway there are various interesting things to=
 say about this contract as a bet on inflation and <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS=
9zcG9ydHMvYmFzZWJhbGwvc2hvaGVpLW9odGFuaXMtZG9kZ2Vycy1jb250cmFjdC1mZWF0dXJlc=
y1qZXJvbWUtcG93ZWxsLWFzLW12cC0zMTllYzQ3NT9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzag/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB31e4f780" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> interest rates</a> and taxes, but my colleague J=
ohn Authers already said them, so I will refer you to <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTItMTIvc2hvaGVpLW9odGFuaS1zLWNvbn=
RyYWN0LXNob3VsZC1iZWNvbWUtYS1jYXNlLXN0dWR5LWZvci1tYmFzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMTQyM=
19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
ZXJtPTIzMTIxNCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf7f=
8f872" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  his column</a>. But a number of readers have asked me abou=
t the <em>credit risk</em>=C2=A0of the contract: Substantially all of Ohtan=
i=E2=80=99s money comes in the form of payments from the Dodgers 10 to 20=
=C2=A0years from now, and what if they default? What if they don=E2=80=99t =
make enough money to pay him? What if he retires in 2034, they have no mone=
y to spend on good players (because they are paying him) and they can=E2=80=
=99t sell enough tickets to pay his deferred comp?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t have a great answer. Major Lea=
gue Baseball, and its players, have definitely thought about this. The curr=
ent <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.25739=
8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubWxicGxheWVycy5jb20vY2Jh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1cdbab5=
b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> Collective Bargaining Agreement</a>=C2=A0has a provision (Art=
icle XVI) covering deferred compensation, which provides that deferred comp=
ensation =E2=80=9Cmust be fully funded by the Club, in an amount equal to t=
he present value of the total deferred compensation amount,=E2=80=9D within=
 two years after it was earned. In Ohtani=E2=80=99s case I think this means=
 that the Dodgers have to fund roughly $46 million a year starting in 2026.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9CFund=E2=80=9D means that the Dodgers have to set aside =
=E2=80=9Cunencumbered assets comprising cash or cash equivalents and/or reg=
istered and unrestricted readily marketable securities=E2=80=9D that are =
=E2=80=9Cexclusively for the uses and purposes of satisfying the deferred c=
ompensation obligation.=E2=80=9D So while he is playing, they will need to =
put aside money to pay him, and I suppose if they don=E2=80=99t he can go f=
ind a higher (or, lower but more creditworthy) bidder.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand the CBA does not require the=
=C2=A0money to be held in escrow for him: It=E2=80=99s just money on the Do=
dgers=E2=80=99 balance sheet, =E2=80=9Csubject to the claims of the Club=E2=
=80=99s general creditors.=E2=80=9D Though perhaps his contract has stricte=
r terms. Otherwise, Ohtani=E2=80=99s bet is something like =E2=80=9Cif the =
Dodgers set aside the money for me, I=E2=80=99ll probably get it, because i=
t=E2=80=99s not like baseball teams have a ton of liabilities=C2=A0<em>othe=
r=C2=A0</em>than deferred comp, so even if they go bankrupt I=E2=80=99ll be=
 the main claimant on that pot of money.=E2=80=9D Which is, you know, proba=
bly fine? Not ironclad? Not necessarily a calculation that I would bet half=
 a billion dollars on but I am, for a great many reasons, not a successful =
professional athlete.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How would you hedge this risk? You can=E2=80=
=99t really short a baseball team, or buy credit default swaps. You could b=
uy index credit default swaps to hedge against widespread credit defaults, =
but that=E2=80=99s not really what you want: The bad state of the world her=
e is not so much =E2=80=9Ca lot of malls go bankrupt=E2=80=9D as it is =E2=
=80=9Cbaseball stops being popular in the US.=E2=80=9D If I were him I=E2=
=80=99d buy, like, Manchester United stock as a hedge.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also the other obvious question here is, what =
if Ohtani would like to live on more than $2 million a year, now? Sure it i=
s nice to have a $680 million nest egg for retirement, but he is a famous s=
uccessful baseball player,=C2=A0shouldn=E2=80=99t he be having more than $2=
 million worth of fun now? I wonder if he can get a bank to lend him money =
against that $680 million?<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> Maybe the bank can figure out the credit risk.</p>
