<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So here=E2=80=99s a question: In May 2022, whe=
n Elon Musk started tweeting=C2=A0nonsense about how he was canceling the d=
eal for spam bots, was that=C2=A0<em>securities fraud? </em>There are argum=
ents both ways. On the one hand:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everything is securities fraud, I keep=
 saying around here.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He was tweeti=
ng false statements about a public company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">The stock did go down. Twitter=E2=80=99s stock fell 9.7%, from $4=
5.08 to $40.72, the day Musk tweeted =E2=80=9Ctemporarily on hold.=E2=80=9D=
 It closed as low ast $32.65 in July.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">If you bought the stock in the low $50s in early May, because Mus=
k had signed a deal to buy it for $54.20, and then sold it in the low $30s =
in July, because Musk was saying that he would get out of the deal, you rea=
lly were=C2=A0<em>deceived=C2=A0</em>(he was not getting out of the deal), =
and you did lose money.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, it=E2=80=99s a weird form o=
f securities fraud. At the time he did these tweets, Musk really did have a=
 binding contract to buy every share of Twitter at $54.20 per share, and he=
 ended up doing that. His false tweets didn=E2=80=99t make him any money. I=
t=E2=80=99s not like he was short Twitter and profited when its price crash=
ed. He was long Twitter and this all ended up just being a costly nuisance =
for him.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, you could argue that he had an economic=
 motive to tank the stock. The motive is that he was=C2=A0<em>trying to ren=
egotiate the deal:=C2=A0</em>He knew he was overpaying for Twitter, and he =
was hoping that, by threatening to walk away from the deal, he could convin=
ce Twitter=E2=80=99s board to agree to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTEvdGhlLXByaWNlLW9mLW5vdC1idXlpbmctdHdpdHRlc=
j9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEyMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBd23fdc4d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> sell to him at a lower price</a>. The =
noisier he was about walking away, the more that threat would feel real. An=
d=C2=A0<em>the=C2=A0more the price fell</em>, the scarier the threat would =
be: Twitter=E2=80=99s board could look at the stock at $32.65 per share and=
 say =E2=80=9C(1) the market thinks he might get out of this and (2) if he =
does get out of it the stock will really tank, so (3) it would be a good id=
ea for=C2=A0us to sign a new ironclad deal at $45.=E2=80=9D And then he=E2=
=80=99d save some money.=C2=A0<em>By manipulating the stock</em>, he could =
save himself billions of dollars in a renegotiated deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway some Twitter shareholders did sue Musk,=
 claiming that he committed securities fraud =E2=80=9Cby making multiple mi=
sstatements to artificially depress the price of Twitter stock and to press=
ure Twitter to lower the price Defendant would have to pay to acquire it.=
=E2=80=9D He filed a motion to dismiss the lawsuit, and on Monday a federal=
 judge partly denied that motion, letting the lawsuit go forward. Here is <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33697175.257398/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JsTHRZej=
Bmc3lKVS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB090ce79a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the judge=E2=80=99=
s opinion</a>, finding=C2=A0that the shareholders have made a case that sev=
eral of Musk=E2=80=99s tweets were false or misleading, that he =E2=80=9C=
=E2=80=98had the motive and opportunity to commit the fraud=E2=80=99=C2=A0t=
o get out of the Merger Agreement because of the large price decline of Tes=
la stock and the realization that =E2=80=98he had greatly overpaid for Twit=
ter by agreeing to buy it shortly before a significant market decline,=E2=
=80=99=E2=80=9D and that the shareholders lost money due to his fraud by se=
lling at depressed prices during the nonsense.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess that=E2=80=99s all reasonable. The jud=
ge does find that some of Musk=E2=80=99s statements aren=E2=80=99t fraud. F=
or instance, Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers sent various letters to Twitter termina=
ting the deal; those letters were also mostly nonsense, and the shareholder=
s argue that they were fraud. The judge disagrees:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plaintiffs do not adequately speci=
fy which statements within the various letters are misleading or state the =
reason or reasons why they are. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Plaintiffs also generally al=
lege that Defendant=E2=80=99s motive in sending letters requesting data was=
 to create uncertainty and the requests were a =E2=80=9Cruse.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=A6 But, again, Plaintiffs do not point to an objectively verifiable aff=
irmative statement or misleading omission. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The Court is not =
convinced that Defendant=E2=80=99s entry into a legal dispute with Twitter,=
 and statements made in support thereof, =E2=80=9Ccreate an impression of a=
 state of affairs that differs in a material way from the one that actually=
 exists.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This also seems right to me? It would be odd t=
o find that it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>fraud=C2=A0</em>to fight Twitter in court=
. Musk fought Twitter in court, and the stakes were that if he won he would=
n=E2=80=99t have to buy Twitter and if he lost he would. He lost. Along the=
 way, Twitter stockholders made bets on whether he=E2=80=99d win or lose: T=
hey sold stock thinking he=E2=80=99d win, or bought it thinking he=E2=80=99=
d lose. If they were wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they overestimated his chances=
 of winning, because of the arguments that he made, which sounded good but =
were not =E2=80=94=C2=A0then they lost money. But it seems odd for them to=
=C2=A0<em>sue=C2=A0</em>him for making those arguments. He was doing the be=
st he could to win in court; it=E2=80=99s not his problem if people believe=
d him.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there is a tension here. If Musk files a=
 legal document saying =E2=80=9Ctoo many bots,=E2=80=9D that=E2=80=99s not =
securities fraud; if he sends a tweet saying =E2=80=9Ctoo many bots,=E2=80=
=9D that is? Musk does most of his litigation on Twitter, so it is strange =
to draw this distinction. Possibly the answer is =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t do =
your litigation on Twitter.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also I should say that the judge goes through =
several of Musk=E2=80=99s bad tweets, concludes that some of them are plaus=
ibly false and misleading and thus can support a lawsuit, but also conclude=
s that some are not. For instance, the May 13, 2022, =E2=80=9Ctemporarily o=
n hold=E2=80=9D tweet can be securities fraud. But on May 16, 2022, Twitter=
=E2=80=99s then chief executive officer, Parag Agrawal, tweeted a measured =
and sensible explanation of how Twitter estimates bot accounts, and =E2=80=
=9CDefendant responded with a tweet of a poop emoji.=E2=80=9D That poop emo=
ji has already <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/336=
97175.257398/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tYXR0X2xldmluZS9zdGF0dXMvMTU0Njk3MD=
